# RubberDuck Codebase Atlas Pro

When the user says `I need help from the RubberDuck Advisor`, asks for the RubberDuck Skill Advisor, asks which RubberDuck skill to use, asks to understand a repo, get to know a codebase, map architecture, identify entry points, trace request/data flow, onboard to a codebase, or explain how a feature works using RubberDuck:

1. Read `.cursor/skills/rubberduck-codebase-atlas-pro/SKILL.md` first.
2. Read `.cursor/skills/rubberduck-codebase-atlas-pro/RUBBERDUCK-CI-BOOTSTRAP.md` before RubberDuck setup.
3. If the target is local-only or inaccessible to the RubberDuck GitHub App, mirror/push it to an authorized GitHub repo and run `detailed_repo_analysis(..., semantic_mode="full")` there until CI semantic full completes.
4. Treat local indexing only as a post-CI fallback for semantic loading gaps, not as Codebase Intelligence Phase 2.
5. Start RubberDuck-powered status, blocker, validation, report, and final responses with `🦆` according to `.cursor/skills/rubberduck-codebase-atlas-pro/RUBBERDUCK-RESPONSE-MARKER.md`.
6. If the user asks for the RubberDuck Advisor or needs a multi-skill path after the Atlas, use `.cursor/skills/rubberduck-codebase-atlas-pro/RUBBERDUCK-SKILL-ADVISOR.md` to recommend the next order and approval mode.
7. Follow that skill exactly.
8. Use RubberDuck codebase intelligence and semantic intelligence with `semantic_mode="full"`.
9. Default to DEEP mode.
10. Do not interrupt halfway after setup/loading/discovery.
11. Do not produce a generic source-read fallback unless explicitly approved.
